MADALA Mishack Mahlangu (67) will now sleep peacefully at night after finally having his own tombstone on his wife’s grave. “I’m happy the people who put a tombstone on my wife’s grave have come forward. I will finally put a tombstone on my wife’s grave on Good Friday.” The madala from Tweefontein, Mpumalanga thanked Daily Sun for locating the owners of the tombstone. His story was published on 5 January. On 24 December, the madala went to visit his wife’s grave in Einel 1 cemetery and was shocked to find a tombstone on it. “The family has come forward after reading about my plea in the People’s Paper. They have apologised for the mistake and promised to remove the tombstone and fix the grave,” he said. “I have accepted that they made a mistake.I think my wife was also shocked by the tombstone from strangers.” Vusi Masango (40) told the SunTeam his family has apologised for the big mistake. “The company that put up the tombstone will remove it and fix the grave. My family will have to work out where exactly the grave of my great grandmother isThe unveiling ceremony will have to wait because we can’t repeat the same mistake,” said Masango. Madala Mishack said he buried his wife Martha Mbonani next to his mother’s grave after she died in 1996. He cleans the graves twice a year – on Good Friday and in December. Sangoma Mehlwemamba Sikhosana said if the family is struggling to locate their grave they must get a goat. “The family must first appease the ancestors then get a goat. They must take it to the cemetery and ask the goat to find the grave they are looking for. “The goat will go straight to the grave and fall asleep on top of it,” he said.